Does this work for IPv6 as well ?
I don't know for sure, but I would expect it to.
Done
Ed, Is it better to check this runtime? If there is no DNS server set on the system (Static/Dynamic DNS server) then use the boost::asio resolver. Else use the crow::async_resolver
No, because if it's used at runtime, it has requirements on compile time dependencies, which is the point of this patch (to be able to make dbus optional).
Ack. So, whoever needs to use the dbus way (existing one), then they have to enable this compiler flag.
The dbus resolver is the default.  Whoever wants to use the dbus way doesn't have to make any changes.
Ack
Should this be private?
Ack
@carson, I'm really not a huge fan of this pattern, but I"m a little at a loss;  Any ideas on how to do it better?

Why do we have to pass the io_context instead of just retrieving it when HttpClient is constructed like were were doing before?  The compiler option should prevent the mismatch between resolver and context if I'm understanding this correctly.

> Why do we have to pass the io_context instead of just retrieving it when HttpClient is constructed like were were doing before?

Because the dns resolver needs an io context.  technically both resolvers do, but the Dbus resolver relies on the fact that the dbus connection is a global.

>  The compiler option should prevent the mismatch between resolver and context if I'm understanding this correctly.

> Because the dns resolver needs an io context. technically both resolvers do, but the Dbus resolver relies on the fact that the dbus connection is a global.
And that's not returned by calling "crow::connections::systemBus->get_io_context();" ?
Done
If httpClientSingleton is null, then call initialize and return the httpClientSingleton object
httpSingleton can't be initialized without an io_service, and not all contexts have an io_service.
Done
What is open compute project IMA again? Might be worth spelling out
Spelled it out.
Moving this file under the compiler flag, will make this flag necessary for boost::asio::ip::tcp::resolver as well correct?

I'm not sure why this would make this flag necessary for boost::asio::ip::tcp::resolver

the intent of this is that if the flag is not enabled, none of the code, including the includes, will be compiled.
Ack
